Well, Americans usually are.

246
00:25:13,393 --> 00:25:15,793
Says the white South African?

247
00:25:16,829 --> 00:25:18,820
l'm from Rhodesia.

248
00:25:20,667 --> 00:25:23,158
We say Zimbabwe now,
don't we?

249
00:25:23,336 --> 00:25:26,601
-Do we?
-Last time l checked.

250
00:25:26,773 --> 00:25:28,934
Don't tell me,
you're here to make a difference.

251
00:25:29,108 --> 00:25:32,339
-And you're here to make a buck?
-l'm here for lack of a better idea.

252
00:25:33,179 --> 00:25:34,976
-That's a shame.
-Not really.

253
00:25:35,148 --> 00:25:37,412
Peace Corps types only
stay around long enough...

254
00:25:37,584 --> 00:25:39,484
...to realize they're not helping anyone.

255
00:25:39,652 --> 00:25:41,517
Government only wants
to stay in power...

256
00:25:41,688 --> 00:25:44,589
...until they've stolen enough
to go into exile somewhere else.

257
00:25:44,757 --> 00:25:47,385
And the rebels, they're not sure
they want to take over.

258
00:25:47,560 --> 00:25:49,892
Otherwise,
they'd have to govern this mess.

259
00:25:50,063 --> 00:25:52,361
-But TlA, right, M'Ed?
-TlA.

260
00:25:52,532 --> 00:25:53,760
What's TlA?

261
00:25:54,400 --> 00:25:58,302
-''This is Africa,'' huh?
-Right.

262
00:25:58,871 --> 00:26:01,339
-You want another?
-Sure.

263
00:26:05,144 --> 00:26:07,669
So which one are you?

264
00:26:09,148 --> 00:26:12,413
-Smuggler?
-Am l?

265
00:26:12,585 --> 00:26:15,520
Somehow you don't strike me
as the UNlCEF type.

266
00:26:16,556 --> 00:26:18,524
How about soldier of fortune?

267
00:26:18,992 --> 00:26:21,552
Or is that too much of a cliche?

268
00:26:21,728 --> 00:26:23,059
Diamonds?

269
00:26:23,763 --> 00:26:27,358
-lf l told you l was a missionary...?
-For Van De Kaap?

270
00:26:29,068 --> 00:26:31,662
Better watch that type of talk,
Miss Bowen.

271
00:26:31,838 --> 00:26:34,932
ln America, it's bling-bling,
but out here, it's bling-bang, huh?

272
00:26:35,208 --> 00:26:38,336
l wouldn't want you
getting in any trouble.

273
00:26:39,612 --> 00:26:41,876
How much trouble
do you think l would get into...

274
00:26:42,048 --> 00:26:45,313
...for talking about blood diamonds?

275
00:26:48,121 --> 00:26:51,181
-You're a journalist.
-That's right.

276
00:26:55,128 --> 00:26:56,720
Piss off, huh?

277
00:27:01,067 --> 00:27:04,332
For five years, this country has reported
almost no diamond exports...

278
00:27:04,504 --> 00:27:08,167
...while Liberia, right next door,
has exported 2 billion dollars' worth.

279
00:27:08,341 --> 00:27:11,367
Very odd, considering that Liberia
has no diamonds to speak of.

280
00:27:11,544 --> 00:27:12,533
l'm shocked.

281
00:27:12,712 --> 00:27:16,045
Van De Kaap denies trading blood
diamonds, but admits it's impossible...

282
00:27:16,215 --> 00:27:20,549
...to tell where a diamond comes from
unless their smuggler gets caught.

283
00:27:20,720 --> 00:27:22,415
What do you want from me, huh?

284
00:27:22,588 --> 00:27:27,116
You know all about Van De Kaap.
Help me out. Off the record.

285
00:27:27,360 --> 00:27:31,820
Well, off the record, l like to get kissed
before l get fucked, huh?

286
00:27:34,400 --> 00:27:35,594
Shit.

287
00:28:08,935 --> 00:28:12,427
-Cordell. How is it, Shona?
-Long time, pal.

288
00:28:12,605 --> 00:28:15,972
-How's Alice?
-She's well, thanks.

289
00:28:16,142 --> 00:28:17,973
Tim must be in school, right?

290
00:28:18,144 --> 00:28:20,476
-Big kids, big problems, you know?
-Yeah, yeah.

291
00:28:20,646 --> 00:28:23,240
l heard you got into a spot of trouble
in the bush, huh?

292
00:28:23,416 --> 00:28:25,816
Well, you know the bush, right, bru?

293
00:28:26,586 --> 00:28:29,146
-Company doing well?
-Can't complain.

294
00:28:29,322 --> 00:28:31,950
Eleven wars in the continent.
We're keeping busy.

295
00:28:32,125 --> 00:28:34,559
So, what, you're here on holiday, huh?

296
00:28:36,262 --> 00:28:38,162
-How's the colonel?
-He sends his regards.

297
00:28:38,331 --> 00:28:42,028
Good, good. Score us a loose, huh?

298
00:28:43,136 --> 00:28:45,331
Smoking will kill you, bru.

299
00:28:45,605 --> 00:28:46,833
Only if l live, right?

300
00:28:52,178 --> 00:28:54,078
That's for breaking my TV, bru.

301
00:28:58,951 --> 00:29:02,478
Tell the colonel he'll get his money.
l'll come see him soon.

302
00:29:09,228 --> 00:29:10,456
Ten more.

303
00:29:10,630 --> 00:29:13,531
Come. Come.

304
00:29:19,639 --> 00:29:21,129
Go on.

305
00:29:35,321 --> 00:29:39,257
Dia. Dia. Come here.
Get away from there.

306
00:29:39,859 --> 00:29:42,521
Go. Go, Mama.

307
00:29:42,695 --> 00:29:44,629
Stay down.

308
00:29:48,367 --> 00:29:49,857
Please...

309
00:29:50,236 --> 00:29:53,103
l must talk to someone. My family's
name is not on the list.

310
00:29:53,406 --> 00:29:54,805
Go to Kissy, there is another list.

311
00:29:55,374 --> 00:29:57,171
l have been to Kissy, and Waterloo, and
Port Loko, and--

312
00:29:57,577 --> 00:29:59,636
Talk to the whites.

313
00:30:02,748 --> 00:30:04,409
Excuse me,
my name's Solomon Vandy--

314
00:30:04,584 --> 00:30:06,677
-Check the list.
-l have checked the list.

315
00:30:06,853 --> 00:30:11,313
-File papers at the Office for Refugees.
-Sir, l have filed papers with the office.

316
00:30:11,491 --> 00:30:13,482
Then God help you,
because l can't.

317
00:30:13,659 --> 00:30:14,717
-Please, sir--
-Next.

318
00:30:14,894 --> 00:30:17,021
-Sir-- Sir, no, please.
-Hey, hey. Me, me, me.

319
00:30:17,196 --> 00:30:20,962
Husband here. One year we look.

320
00:30:25,471 --> 00:30:27,632
Hurry, Mom. Go.

321
00:30:32,812 --> 00:30:34,177
Dia! Dia!

322
00:30:34,347 --> 00:30:35,336
-Jassie!
-Dia!

323
00:30:35,515 --> 00:30:37,107
-Mama!
-Dia!

324
00:30:37,283 --> 00:30:39,444
Jassie! Mama!

325
00:30:53,099 --> 00:30:55,863
Cape Town,
South Africa

326
00:31:01,707 --> 00:31:04,540
He's been waiting.
What took you?

327
00:31:05,244 --> 00:31:08,611
What are you gonna do,
shoot me right here, huh, Shona?

328
00:31:08,781 --> 00:31:11,875
Now, don't be a wanker, man. Get in.

329
00:31:43,950 --> 00:31:46,350
-Hello, Danny.
-Colonel.

330
00:31:46,519 --> 00:31:48,316
You look well.

331
00:31:48,487 --> 00:31:51,650
Clean living and a pure heart,
l suppose, huh?

332
00:31:51,991 --> 00:31:53,686
Walk with me.

333
00:31:55,461 --> 00:31:58,294
lt seems the rebels have taken back
the diamond fields, Danny.

334
00:31:58,464 --> 00:32:00,796
The government
of Sierra Leone has contracted us...

335
00:32:00,967 --> 00:32:02,935
...to go in there
and take the rebels down.

336
00:32:03,102 --> 00:32:04,694
So you sell the rebels weapons...

337
00:32:04,870 --> 00:32:07,532
...the government hires you
when they use them? Nice, sir.

338
00:32:08,007 --> 00:32:10,874
l assume you're asking
for mining concessions, huh?

339
00:32:11,043 --> 00:32:14,171
We save the government,
they show their gratitude.

340
00:32:14,347 --> 00:32:16,645
And you get rich, right?

341
00:32:20,953 --> 00:32:22,511
How long have l known you, Danny?

342
00:32:22,955 --> 00:32:26,118
l was.... l was 1 9, sir.

343
00:32:26,359 --> 00:32:30,887
And you survived.
A lot of boys didn't. Why is that?

344
00:32:32,298 --> 00:32:34,960
Just lucky, l guess.

345
00:32:36,869 --> 00:32:41,738
No, you were a good soldier.
But l made you better, didn't l?

346
00:32:45,111 --> 00:32:46,544
Yes, sir. Yes, you did.

347
00:32:46,712 --> 00:32:49,738
And over the years,
didn't l protect you...

348
00:32:50,149 --> 00:32:54,108
...teach you about diamonds,
cut you in on the deals?

349
00:32:54,286 --> 00:32:57,949
-Some might call it that, yeah.
-But not you...

350
00:32:58,924 --> 00:33:02,587
...because you done with me now, eh?
On to bigger things.

351
00:33:05,731 --> 00:33:08,199
l need a man that knows
his way around up there.

352
00:33:08,367 --> 00:33:12,133
Unless, of course,
you wanna cut me in. Something pink?

353
00:33:13,205 --> 00:33:14,729
Sir....

354
00:33:14,907 --> 00:33:17,034
Our deal went bad,
and you owe me money.

355
00:33:17,209 --> 00:33:18,938
l'll take a stone as payment.

356
00:33:19,111 --> 00:33:22,979
Look, do you think if l found a stone
like that, l'd still be on this continent?

357
00:33:23,149 --> 00:33:26,983
-Come on.
-Danny, give me your hand.

358
00:33:29,989 --> 00:33:33,720
That's red earth. lt's in our skin.

359
00:33:34,193 --> 00:33:36,593
The Shona say the color
comes from all the blood...

360
00:33:36,762 --> 00:33:39,322
...that's being spilled
fighting over the land.

361
00:33:41,367 --> 00:33:45,929
This is home.
You'll never leave Africa.

362
00:33:48,708 --> 00:33:51,370
lf you say so, sir.

363
00:34:06,892 --> 00:34:10,521
So, what did you do, bury it?

364
00:34:11,731 --> 00:34:15,292
Yeah. Yeah, l would have
buried it, huh?

365
00:34:15,468 --> 00:34:19,495
-What are you talking about?
-What am l talking about? Come on, bru.

366
00:34:19,672 --> 00:34:21,105
l'm late for work.

367
00:34:21,273 --> 00:34:23,798
Pink, huh? The biggest one
he'd ever seen.

368
00:34:23,976 --> 00:34:26,103
You were in the mining camps,
weren't you, bru?

369
00:34:26,278 --> 00:34:29,770
Why else would that rebel with
the bandaged eye make up such a story?

370
00:34:29,949 --> 00:34:32,179
Go ask him.

371
00:34:46,499 --> 00:34:47,727
Thank you.

372
00:34:57,376 --> 00:35:00,174
Your mothers and fathers,
your brothers and sisters are dead.

373
00:35:00,346 --> 00:35:02,211
-You are dead! You have been reborn.
-No!

374
00:35:02,381 --> 00:35:05,612
-We are your family now.
-No! No!

375
00:35:13,492 --> 00:35:15,824
Your parents are weak.

376
00:35:16,395 --> 00:35:20,832
They're the farmers.
They're the fishermen.

377
00:35:21,333 --> 00:35:24,894
They've done nothing
but suck the blood from this country.

378
00:35:26,272 --> 00:35:30,732
But you are the heroes
who will save this nation.

379
00:35:31,010 --> 00:35:32,978
You are not children anymore.

380
00:35:33,979 --> 00:35:35,913
You're men.

381
00:35:38,117 --> 00:35:41,280
No one has ever given you respect...

382
00:35:41,453 --> 00:35:44,547
...but with this in your hand,
they go fear you.

383
00:35:44,723 --> 00:35:47,214
lf you do not get
the respect you deserve...

384
00:35:47,393 --> 00:35:49,691
...you will take it
by shedding their blood.

385
00:35:49,862 --> 00:35:53,821
-Repeat after me, shed their blood.
-Shed their blood.

386
00:35:53,999 --> 00:35:57,059
-Louder! Shed their blood! Shed their blood!
-Shed their blood!

387
00:35:57,236 --> 00:36:00,364
Make them hear you in Freetown.
Shed their blood! Shed their blood!

388
00:36:00,539 --> 00:36:03,099
Shed their blood! Shed their blood!
Shed their blood!

389
00:36:03,275 --> 00:36:06,176
-Dia Vandy, stand up.
-Shed their blood! Shed their blood!

390
00:36:06,345 --> 00:36:09,246
-Shed their blood! Shed their blood!
-Put your hand on the gun.

391
00:36:09,415 --> 00:36:11,007
Shed their blood!
Shed their blood!

392
00:36:11,183 --> 00:36:12,775
Shed their blood!
Shed their blood!

393
00:36:12,952 --> 00:36:15,978
-Shed their blood! Shed their blood!
-Now squeeze the trigger.

394
00:36:16,522 --> 00:36:20,925
Come on, Dia. Pull the trigger.
Pull the trigger!

395
00:36:55,060 --> 00:36:59,622
l know, l know.
lt's hard to be a man.

396
00:37:00,366 --> 00:37:02,891
Sit up. Come.

397
00:37:03,068 --> 00:37:07,368
But you are a soldier
of the revolution now.

398
00:37:07,573 --> 00:37:10,440
And l am your commander.

399
00:37:10,943 --> 00:37:12,808
Whatever you need...

400
00:37:12,978 --> 00:37:16,209
...guns, CDs, food...

401
00:37:16,382 --> 00:37:20,045
...come to me.
l will take care of you.

402
00:37:23,355 --> 00:37:29,760
Today, you are promoted
to the rank of captain.

403
00:37:34,366 --> 00:37:36,357
Dia Vandy...

404
00:37:37,970 --> 00:37:39,801
...boss man.

405
00:37:57,556 --> 00:37:59,183
How's it, bru?

406
00:37:59,725 --> 00:38:02,888
-You got something for me, huh?
-Yeah.

407
00:38:03,662 --> 00:38:07,063
-So, what's new, M'Ed?
-Fucking RUF.

408
00:38:07,232 --> 00:38:09,757
Tried to hit the government building
across the street.

409
00:38:09,935 --> 00:38:14,599
Shit, man, half the people
be soldiers today, RUF tomorrow.

410
00:38:14,773 --> 00:38:18,174
-Might be time to get your family out, huh?
-And go where?

411
00:38:18,344 --> 00:38:22,075
Just fire up the chopper
and fly away like you people?

412
00:38:22,448 --> 00:38:24,279
This my country, man.

413
00:38:24,450 --> 00:38:27,908
We here long before you came,
long after you gone.

414
00:38:36,929 --> 00:38:40,092
-Hi. l'm Maddy Bowen.
-How about you dance with me?

415
00:38:40,265 --> 00:38:43,632
-No, l don't dance.
-Neither do l. Come on.

416
00:38:48,841 --> 00:38:51,241
-So, Danny....
-Archer.

417
00:38:51,543 --> 00:38:52,601
Archer.

418
00:38:53,612 --> 00:38:57,173
When did you first start
moving stones? Was it Angola?

419
00:38:58,951 --> 00:39:03,547
Then you did the whole
mercenary thing. Was that fun?

420
00:39:05,090 --> 00:39:08,753
So, what are you?
Nihilist? Opportunist?

421
00:39:08,961 --> 00:39:11,088
Maybe l wasn't breast-fed
as a child, huh?

422
00:39:13,232 --> 00:39:15,666
You think l haven't met
people like you before?

423
00:39:15,834 --> 00:39:19,201
-l think you get off on people like me.
-You think?

424
00:39:21,940 --> 00:39:24,465
When did you first start
working for Van De Kaap?

425
00:39:25,044 --> 00:39:26,671
Christ, you never stop, do you?

426
00:39:27,946 --> 00:39:31,313
No, l never stop.

427
00:39:32,017 --> 00:39:33,609
Do you want me to stop?

428
00:39:34,987 --> 00:39:38,889
Why don't we go back to your place,
see what's in the minibar, huh?

429
00:39:39,058 --> 00:39:41,151
l'm a print journalist. l drank it.

430
00:39:42,428 --> 00:39:45,158
ls it possible that you don't care
how many people die...

431
00:39:45,330 --> 00:39:47,230
...because of the deals you do?

432
00:39:47,399 --> 00:39:50,630
People here kill each other as a way of life.
Always been like that.

433
00:39:50,903 --> 00:39:53,736
So you can just watch it
and go about your day?

434
00:39:55,040 --> 00:39:57,133
Maybe we should all just
write about it, then.

435
00:39:57,309 --> 00:39:59,641
Look, thanks for the dance, huh?

436
00:40:01,847 --> 00:40:05,214
-And a shot too, huh, M'Ed?
-Sure.

437
00:40:09,054 --> 00:40:10,351
You're a hard case, huh?

438
00:40:10,522 --> 00:40:13,514
Tell me something,
how long you been here in Africa, huh?

439
00:40:13,725 --> 00:40:17,024
Three months. And before that,
Afghanistan and Bosnia.

440
00:40:17,329 --> 00:40:19,422
You come here
with your laptop computer...

441
00:40:19,598 --> 00:40:23,534
...and your malaria medicine
and your little bottles of hand sanitizer.

442
00:40:24,303 --> 00:40:27,329
Think you're gonna change
the outcome, huh?

443
00:40:27,506 --> 00:40:30,100
Let me tell you something.
You sell blood diamonds too.

444
00:40:30,275 --> 00:40:31,765
-Really?
-Yeah.

445
00:40:31,944 --> 00:40:32,933
Tell me, how is that?

446
00:40:33,112 --> 00:40:35,376
Who do you think buys
the stones that l bring out?

447
00:40:35,547 --> 00:40:39,176
Dreamy American girls who all want
a storybook wedding and a big, shiny rock...

448
00:40:39,351 --> 00:40:42,912
...like the ones in the advertisements
of your politically-correct magazines.

449
00:40:43,088 --> 00:40:46,080
So, please, don't come here
and make judgments on me, all right?

450
00:40:47,493 --> 00:40:51,793
l provide a service. The world wants what
we have, and they want it cheap.

451
00:40:51,964 --> 00:40:55,195
We're in business together.
Get over yourself, darling.

452
00:40:55,667 --> 00:40:59,763
Okay, just to clarify, not all American girls
want a storybook wedding...

453
00:40:59,938 --> 00:41:02,839
...just like not all Africans kill each other
as a way of life.

454
00:41:03,008 --> 00:41:05,408
And yeah, it's a shit, shit world,
but you know what?

455
00:41:05,577 --> 00:41:09,445
Good things are done every day,
just, apparently, not by you.

456
00:41:11,049 --> 00:41:14,075
This place is about to explode.

457
00:41:14,353 --> 00:41:16,378
l wanna spend my time
with someone else.

458
00:41:27,466 --> 00:41:30,492
You are listening to BBC World Service.

459
00:41:30,669 --> 00:41:34,400
In Sierra Leone, Revolutionary United Front
forces have been sighted...

460
00:41:34,573 --> 00:41:37,303
...within 1 0 kilometers
of the capital city of Freetown.

461
00:41:37,476 --> 00:41:40,138
The minister of the interior
has expressed confidence...

462
00:41:40,312 --> 00:41:42,678
...that the government troops
can repel the attack.

463
00:41:42,848 --> 00:41:46,113
All foreign nationals are being advised
to leave the country.

464
00:41:46,285 --> 00:41:48,446
There are also unconfirmed reports...

465
00:41:48,620 --> 00:41:52,681
...that atrocities are being committed by
both sides in the rapidly worsening situation.

466
00:41:52,858 --> 00:41:56,794
The United Nations has described
the refugee situation as critical.

467
00:42:08,373 --> 00:42:10,773
Don't tell me you're gonna try
and sell it yourself.

468
00:42:10,943 --> 00:42:13,468
To who?
And for what price, my friend?

469
00:42:13,645 --> 00:42:15,670
You need my help,
whether you like it or not.

470
00:42:15,847 --> 00:42:18,907
-What are you talking about?
-Here, let me help you with that.

471
00:42:19,084 --> 00:42:22,952
You hear that? You hear that?
They came into the city overnight.

472
00:42:23,121 --> 00:42:25,419
lt's started.
What are you gonna do now, huh?

473
00:42:25,591 --> 00:42:29,891
Listen, the right stone can buy anything.
lnformation, safety, even freedom.

474
00:42:30,062 --> 00:42:32,496
But a big stone does not stay secret
for very long.

475
00:42:32,664 --> 00:42:35,929
The moment you tell anyone about it,
your life is absolutely worthless.

476
00:42:36,101 --> 00:42:39,229
The only reason you're alive is
you haven't told anyone where it is.

477
00:42:39,404 --> 00:42:40,666
Am l right? Am l?

478
00:42:41,073 --> 00:42:43,098
Who do you think got you
out of jail, huh?

479
00:42:43,275 --> 00:42:46,335
-That makes us partners.
